    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1950-09-26T23:59:59-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1950-09-26T00:00:00-05:00" n="283"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d283">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">394.31/9–2650</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">Memorandum of Conversation, by Mr. Lucius D. Battle of the
                        Executive Secretariat of the Department of State</hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <seg rendition="#left">
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">confidential</hi>
                    </seg>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">[<placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Washington</hi>
                        </placeName>,] <date calendar="gregorian" when="1950-09-26">September 26,
                            1950</date>.</dateline>
                </opener>
                <table>
                    <row>
                        <cell rendition="#nowrap">Participants:</cell>
                        <cell>Mr. Acheson</cell>
                    </row>
                    <row>
                        <cell/>
                        <cell>Mr. Bevin<note n="1" xml:id="d283fn1">Ernest Bevin, British Secretary
                                of State for Foreign Affairs.</note>
                        </cell>
                    </row>
                    <row>
                        <cell/>
                        <cell>Mr. Barclay<note n="2" xml:id="d283fn2">R. E. Barclay, Private
                                Secretary to Mr. Bevin.</note>
                        </cell>
                    </row>
                    <row>
                        <cell/>
                        <cell>Mr. Battle</cell>
                    </row>
                </table>
                <p>In a conversation on other matters, Mr. Bevin mentioned the Torquay tariff
                    negotiations. He said that he hoped that the negotiations <pb facs="0819"
                        n="803" xml:id="pg_803"/> this time would not get in a wrangle on the
                    question of imperial preferences. He said that the issue would not arise. He
                    said the British would do all possible to meet us on other matters but hoped
                    that the question of imperial preferences could be avoided.</p>
                <p>Mr. Acheson said that he would take the matter up with Willard Thorp.<note n="3"
                        xml:id="d283fn3">Willard L. Thorp, Assistant Secretary of State for Economic
                        Affairs, had been designated Chairman of the United States Delegation to the
                        Third Bound of Tariff Negotiations under the General Agreement on Tariffs
                        and Trade. For a list of persons named to the United States Delegation, see
                        Department of State <hi rend="italic">Bulletin</hi>, October 2, 1950, pp.
                        553 ff. The Third Round opened at Torquay, England, on September 28.</note>
                </p>
            </div>
        </body>
